UPDATE designers SET biography = E'Pierre Bonnefille is a French artist, painter, designer and \'Maître d\'Art\' — a title awarded by the French Ministry of Culture to masters of exceptional craft. Born in 1958 in Saint-Quentin and raised partly in the Auvergne region of central France, he developed an early love of nature watching his great-aunt, an archaeologist and painter, at work. A graduate of both the École Boulle and the École Nationale Supérieure des Arts Décoratifs in Paris, he has spent more than three decades creating his own materials from mineral powder, limestone, lava, marble, earth, natural pigments and metallic powders.\n\nhttps://s30964.pcdn.co/introspective-magazine/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/1PierreBonnefille_2-Luca-Bonnefille-1024x683.jpg | | left\n\nBonnefille\'s work defies easy categorisation. He creates monumental Bronze Paintings — richly textured mixed-media works on metallic mesh where bronze powder, carbon, gold and silver leaf produce surfaces that shift between silvery luminescence and firelike warmth depending on the light source. His Meditation Room, an immersive installation composed entirely of these paintings, has travelled from Paris to London, New York and Los Angeles, and was presented at the Musée National des Arts Asiatiques — Guimet during Paris Design Week 2021.\n\nHis process is both original and deeply personal. To create his signature textures, he mixes pigments with sand and ground rock, sometimes applying gold or silver leaf on top, other times stamping the surface with fabric to leave behind what he calls a \'textile fossil.\' His tools are equally unconventional: a Japanese lacquer brush made with human hair, palette knives nearly ten feet wide, and blades with slightly rounded edges for a more gentle effect. He maintains a collection of some hundred iridescent scarab beetles — acquired in Thailand and from the Parisian taxidermy house Deyrolle — whose shells he studies for their extraordinary durability and complexity of colour.\n\nhttps://s30964.pcdn.co/introspective-magazine/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/1Pierre-Bonnefille-Table-haute-polygone-2-%C2%A9IanScigliuzzi-1024x703.gif | | right\n\nBonnefille is perhaps best known for his bespoke murals and decorative surfaces, created for an extraordinary roster of clients. His collaboration with Olivier Gagnère on the Café Marly at the Musée du Louvre — where he suggested wall tones inspired by Pompeii, adding volcanic ashes to the wax polish and passing a hot iron over the finished surface — first brought him widespread international attention. He has since created custom environments for Hermès, Cartier, Loro Piana and Christian Liaigre, as well as monumental commissions including wall panels for the Shard in London and the Paris offices of Clifford Chance. \'Pierre is not just an extraordinary colourist,\' says Denis Montel, director of RDAI, which oversees Hermès boutiques worldwide. \'He also has a great sensitivity to touch and creates materials that are at once strong and delicate.\'\n\nhttps://res.cloudinary.com/dif1oamtj/image/upload/v1774862242/Screen_Shot_2026-03-30_at_5.16.38_PM_ldnx4h.png | | left\n\nIn 2016, he launched his Metamorphosis furniture collection — tables, cabinets, credenzas and shelving systems whose angular shapes and metallic textures were inspired by a collection of copper minerals from ancient African mines he discovered at an antiques dealer. These limited-edition and one-off pieces have been exhibited at Salon Art + Design in New York, PAD London and through galleries including Charles Burnand and L\'Eclaireur. From his atelier in Maisons-Alfort, on the outskirts of Paris, Bonnefille now leads a team of twenty across two workshops and a central Paris showroom.\n\n<strong>\'I have the impression I always do the same thing, but each time in a slightly different fashion.\'</strong> — Pierre Bonnefille, 1stDibs Introspective' WHERE slug = 'pierre-bonnefille';